    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Isaac Leeser Esq</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)"><persName>Mr Selling</persName> called<lb/> for your books and has
                them now in<lb/> his possession. He requested me to state<lb/> that the society is
                unwilling to defray<lb/> my expense <del>oc</del>incurred. It is his intention<lb/>
                to keep the books for a time to see<lb/> if he can get customers. If he cannot<lb/>
                he will return them. The people of <placeName>Hartford</placeName><lb/> will buy
                anything in preference to books.<lb/> I perceive from the paper that <persName>Soln
                    Jacobs</persName><lb/> is about to quit <placeName>Charleston</placeName>. I
                would like to know why. Do you think I would<lb/> have any chance there as lecturer
                Teacher<lb/> &amp;cYours</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author">A Harris</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <date>June 18 1857</date>
            </p>
            <p>The particulars of the murder of <persName>Jackson</persName><lb/> are these. There
                were three brothers two<lb/> of whom were in partnership &amp; kept a store<lb/> The
                kind a youth of 17 peddled for the<lb/> former. The young men were all good<lb/>
                <add>יהודים</add> did no business on <add>שבת</add> or <add>יום טוב</add><lb/> about
                afortnight before the murder</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the three brothers left their business &amp; came<lb/> to
                    <placeName>Hartford</placeName> to keep <add>יאהר צייט</add>.<lb/> On
                    <date>Monday</date> morning the youngest<lb/> brother started with horse &amp;
                wagon<lb/> for the country. After being two<lb/> hours on the road he was met by
                a<lb/> convict named <persName>Jones</persName> formerly a<lb/> clergyman in
                    <placeName>Hartford</placeName> who had<lb/> been convicted for robbery &amp;
                whose<lb/> term of imprisonment expired a day<lb/> or two before. <persName>Mr
                    Jones</persName> it is supposed<lb/> spoke to him about some clothes<lb/> with
                which he peddled &amp; while<lb/>
                <persName>Jackson</persName> turned <del>the</del> round he<lb/> shot him the bullet
                going thro'<lb/> the heart &amp; producing instant death<lb/>
                <persName>Jones</persName> next dragged the body to the river<lb/> and heaped a
                quantity of stones<lb/> round it, mounted the wagon &amp; <sic>road</sic><lb/> up to
                a farmer who knew <persName>Jackson's</persName><lb/> wagon. Suspicion was
                excited,<lb/> search instituted &amp; the discovery<lb/> made.</p>
        </body>
